  {
    "page": 16,
    "block_id": "page_016:block_051",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "while using an equivalent number of input tokens. For runtime, GPT 4.1 - mini and Qwen turbo require the least processing time, DeepSeek V3 takes approximately twice as long, and DeepSeek R1 incurs the highest latency.",
    "bbox": [
      45.459999084472656,
      83.43709564208984,
      440.42730712890625,
      121.1153793334961
    ],
    "reading_order": 51,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "page": 16,
    "block_id": "page_016:block_052",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "RQ3: CaVulner demonstrates high economic feasibility. Using DeepSeek V3, the average cost is only $0.06 per CVE. This confirms that standard LLMs offer a scalable and cost- effective solution for automated vulnerable version identification.",
    "bbox": [
      61.41899871826172,
      134.4370880126953,
      426.2600402832031,
      172.11538696289062
    ],
    "reading_order": 52,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "page": 16,
    "block_id": "page_016:block_053",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "5 Discussion Threats to Validity. In constructing the ground truth, we manually identified the vulnerable versions for each CVE, which may introduce potential inaccuracies. To mitigate this threat, three authors with cybersecurity expertise, including one Ph.D. student and two master’s students, independently examined each CVE based on their domain knowledge and publicly available information. Discrepancies were resolved through collaborative discussion until consensus was reached. On average, six CVEs were processed per day, and the entire process took approximately one month. To capture the complexity of real-world vulnerabilities, our dataset incorporates diverse data qualities. Among the 176 selected CVEs, 58.6% contain low-quality commits with irrelevant messages, 9.9% involve complex fixes that modify more than five files, and 5.7% lack CWE information. Such heterogeneity suggests that CaVulner possesses a significant degree of tolerance toward low-quality input data. LLM Capability and Overhead. Previous approaches to vulnerable version identification were limited in their ability to understand vulnerability semantics and code logic. The emergence of large language models (LLMs) has addressed this limitation by enabling more accurate semantic reasoning. However, LLMs are not always precise and may still produce incorrect results. As LLM technology continues to evolve, its effectiveness in vulnerability analysis is expected to improve further. Although LLM-based identification requires more time compared to traditional methods, the improvement in accuracy makes the additional computational cost acceptable. Other Ecosystems. This study focuses on the Java ecosystem for three reasons. Java is the dominant language in enterprise - level applications, and its vulnerabilities can have far - reaching consequences. For example, Log4Shell vulnerability remains one of the most critical flaws ever discovered [ 15 ]. Moreover, the first author has worked extensively on Java vulnerability research, including zero - day discovery, and possesses deep practical expertise with Java codebases and patch processes. This experience substantially reduces annotation errors when constructing the ground truth of vulnerable versions. Finally, to ensure accurate and efficient extraction of method change patterns from fix commits, we employ a Java AST parsing library. Extending vulnerable - version identification to other ecosystems such as C, C++, and Python represents an important direction for future work.",
    "bbox": [
      45.499000549316406,
      187.39926147460938,
      441.2708435058594,
      537.8843383789062
    ],
    "reading_order": 53,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "page": 16,
